<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="51" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[136,1452,302,1157]" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,493,842,868]" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Distribution and habitat:</emphasis>
—So far, 
<taxonomicName box="[606,842,842,868]" class="Marchantiopsida" family="Ricciaceae" genus="Riccia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Marchantiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="species" species="junghuhniana">
<emphasis box="[606,842,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Riccia junghuhniana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been known from 
<collectingCountry box="[1106,1209,842,868]" name="Australia" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1224,1440,842,869]" country="Australia" name="Northern Territory" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Northern Territory</collectingRegion>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[136,203,878,904]" name="China" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[216,322,878,905]" country="China" name="Zhejiang" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Zhejiang</collectingRegion>
), and 
<collectingCountry box="[386,495,878,904]" name="Indonesia" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry box="[508,596,878,904]" name="Indonesia" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Ambon</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[607,656,878,904]" country="Indonesia" name="Bali" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Bali</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[666,720,879,905]" country="Indonesia" name="Jawa Timur" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Java</collectingRegion>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[767,837,878,904]" name="China" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">China</collectingCountry>
, it grows on moist and shady soil at a low altitude, from 
<quantity box="[136,207,914,941]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.06" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" unit="m" value="306.0">306 m</quantity>
to 
<specimenCount box="[243,321,914,941]" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" type="generic">
<quantity box="[243,317,914,941]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.34" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" unit="m" value="434.0">434 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[136,1452,302,1157]" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,256,950,976]" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Notes</emphasis>
:—The important features of 
<taxonomicName box="[595,832,950,976]" class="Marchantiopsida" family="Ricciaceae" genus="Riccia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Marchantiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" phylum="Marchantiophyta" rank="species" species="junghuhniana">
<emphasis box="[595,832,950,976]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Riccia junghuhniana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
include the 1) monoicy; 2) thalli growing as patches, not in rosettes or hemi-rosettes (
<figureCitation box="[497,621,986,1012]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[136,229,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,209,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,190,1895]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Riccia junghuhniana Nees &amp; Lindenb.A−B. Habit in the field. C−F. SEM micrographs of spores, C−D, proximal face, E−F, distal face. G−N. Light microscopy micrographs, G−J, proximal face, K−N, distal face. O−P. Transverse section of segments. All from Y. Bai et al. 20201101-34 (HSNU)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5843509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5843509/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Fig. 3A–B</figureCitation>
); 3) with narrow air chambers in thallus (
<figureCitation box="[1085,1205,986,1012]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[136,229,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,209,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,190,1895]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Riccia junghuhniana Nees &amp; Lindenb.A−B. Habit in the field. C−F. SEM micrographs of spores, C−D, proximal face, E−F, distal face. G−N. Light microscopy micrographs, G−J, proximal face, K−N, distal face. O−P. Transverse section of segments. All from Y. Bai et al. 20201101-34 (HSNU)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5843509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5843509/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Fig. 3O–P</figureCitation>
); 4) thallus 
<quantity box="[1338,1452,986,1013]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="2.25" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.0">2–2.5 mm</quantity>
wide, 2.6–3.5 times as broad as thick in transverse section (
<figureCitation box="[791,910,1022,1048]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[136,229,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,209,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,190,1895]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Riccia junghuhniana Nees &amp; Lindenb.A−B. Habit in the field. C−F. SEM micrographs of spores, C−D, proximal face, E−F, distal face. G−N. Light microscopy micrographs, G−J, proximal face, K−N, distal face. O−P. Transverse section of segments. All from Y. Bai et al. 20201101-34 (HSNU)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5843509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5843509/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Fig. 3O–P</figureCitation>
); 5) spores 64–85 µm in diameter, with complete alveoli on the distal face, 6–10 areolae across the diameter, with papillate corners (
<figureCitation box="[1078,1290,1058,1085]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[136,229,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,209,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,190,1895]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Riccia junghuhniana Nees &amp; Lindenb.A−B. Habit in the field. C−F. SEM micrographs of spores, C−D, proximal face, E−F, distal face. G−N. Light microscopy micrographs, G−J, proximal face, K−N, distal face. O−P. Transverse section of segments. All from Y. Bai et al. 20201101-34 (HSNU)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5843509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5843509/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Fig. 3E–F &amp; K–N</figureCitation>
), and 6) spore wings 3–4 µm wide, crenulate (
<figureCitation box="[486,609,1094,1120]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="9.[136,229,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,209,1841]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,190,1895]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 3. Riccia junghuhniana Nees &amp; Lindenb.A−B. Habit in the field. C−F. SEM micrographs of spores, C−D, proximal face, E−F, distal face. G−N. Light microscopy micrographs, G−J, proximal face, K−N, distal face. O−P. Transverse section of segments. All from Y. Bai et al. 20201101-34 (HSNU)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5843509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5843509/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Fig. 3C–D</figureCitation>
). The morphological comparison among samples from 
<collectingCountry box="[1223,1290,1094,1120]" name="China" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">China</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1342,1451,1094,1120]" name="Indonesia" pageId="10" pageNumber="51">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
showed that there were no obvious differences in the characters mentioned above.
</paragraph>
